EXECUTIVE SUMMARY

In the digital era, data-driven decision making has become a necessity, providing a competitive advantage for businesses. This study aimed to leverage the Amazon-PQA dataset to uncover insights from customer queries and product information, with the goal of improving product descriptions, customer service, and marketing strategies which revolves around answering the following problem statement:

How can we leverage the Amazon-PQA dataset to understand customer queries and product information better, and use this understanding to improve product descriptions, customer service, and marketing strategies?

The motivation behind this study was not only to enhance sales growth or service but to gain a deeper understanding of our customers and create an enhanced shopping experience tailored to individual preferences and needs.

The methodology involved three main steps: data collection, data preprocessing and exploratory data analysis (EDA), and detailed data analysis & visualization. The data was collected from Amazon Q&A JSON files and loaded into a Spark DataFrame. After data preprocessing and EDA, a more detailed analysis was performed to uncover key insights.

The analysis revealed that the most common product category was unlocked cell phones, and the most common brand name was an empty string, indicating many products are unbranded or the brand is not specified. The item with the most questions was the Fire TV Stick with Alexa Voice Remote, suggesting that this product generates a lot of customer interest or has unclear product descriptions. The majority of the top 10 product categories were tech-related, suggesting a strong customer interest in these areas. The top brands in the dataset were well-known tech giants such as Amazon, Samsung, ASUS, Sony, HP, Apple, Acer, and Dell.

Based on these insights, several recommendations were made for immediate implementation and future work. For immediate implementation, it was recommended to improve product descriptions, enhance customer service, and optimize marketing strategies. A formula for structuring product descriptions was also provided as follows:

[Product Name] + [Key Features] + [Specifications] + [Compatibility Information] + [Usage Instructions] + [Support and Warranty Information]

For future work, it was suggested to conduct temporal analysis, expand analysis to other platforms, incorporate sentiment analysis, personalize customer service, and test and refine recommendations.

This study provides a comprehensive understanding of customer queries and product information, offering valuable insights to improve product descriptions, customer service, and marketing strategies. By implementing the recommendations, Amazon and retailers can enhance their offerings, amplify customer satisfaction, and drive revenue growth.

# Define Global Helper Functions
def preview_df(data_label, df, display_df=True, display_nulls=False):
    """Displays the data label, number of data points and features, columns 
    with null values, and preview of the DataFrame.
    """
    # Calculate the number of data points and features
    num_data_points = df.count()
    num_features = len(df.columns)
    
    # Display the results
    display(HTML(f"<b><span style='color:#f56802;'>Data Label: "
                 f"</span>{data_label}</b>"))
    display(HTML(f"<b><span style='color:#f56802;'>Number of Data Points: "
                 f"</span>{num_data_points:,.0f}</b>"))
    display(HTML(f"<b><span style='color:#f56802;'>Number of Features: "
                 f"</span>{num_features:,.0f}</b>"))
    
    # Iterate over all columns and check for null values
    null_columns = []
    for column in df.columns:
        null_count = df.filter(col(column).isNull()).count()
        if null_count > 0:
            null_columns.append((column, null_count))

    # Create a new DataFrame with columns and their null counts
    if null_columns:    # Check if null_columns is not empty
        null_columns_df = spark.createDataFrame(null_columns, 
                                                ["Column", "Null Count"])
        display(HTML(f"<b><span style='color:#f56802;'>Columns with "
                     f"null values:</span></b>"))
        display(null_columns_df.toPandas())
    else:
        display(HTML(f"<b><span style='color:#f56802;'>No columns with null "
                     f"values</span></b>"))

    # If display_df=True, display 1 sample row of the current dataframe
    if display_df:
        display(HTML(f"<b><span style='color:#f56802;'>Preview of the "
                     f"dataframe:</span></b>"))
        display(df.limit(1).toPandas())


def display_mode(columns):
    """Returns the mode for each specified column (list) in the given 
    PySpark DataFrame.
    
    Args:
        columns (list): List of column names to calculate mode for.
    """
    display(HTML(f'<left><span style="color:gray; font-size:16px"><b>Table'
                 f' 3. </b>Mode: Most Common Values of Specified '
                 f'Columns</span></left>'))
    
    # Calculate mode for each column
    modes = []
    for column in columns:
        mode = pqa_all.groupBy(column).count().orderBy(desc('count')).first()
        modes.append((column, mode[column], mode['count']))

    # Create a Pandas DataFrame from the modes
    df_modes = pd.DataFrame(modes, columns=['Column', 
                                            'Most Common Value', 
                                            'Count'])

    # Display the modes
    display(df_modes)


def plot_top_product_categories(pqa_all):
    """Plots the top 10 product categories based on count."""
    top_categories = (pqa_all
                       .groupBy('product_category')
                       .agg(count('*').alias('count'))
                       .sort('count', ascending=False)
                       .limit(10)
                       .toPandas())

    # Create the vertical bar plot with reversed order
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(8, 6))
    ax.barh(top_categories['product_category'][::-1],  # Reverse the order
            top_categories['count'][::-1],  # Reverse the order of counts
            color=[c_darkorange, c_midorange, c_darkorange, c_darkorange, 
                   c_darkorange, c_midorange, c_orange,  c_darkorange, 
                   c_darkorange, c_orange][::-1])
    ax.set_xlabel('Count (Thousands)', fontsize=16)
    ax.set_ylabel('Product Category', fontsize=16)
    ax.set_title('Tech and Accessories Product Categories Dominate PQA', 
                 fontsize=20, fontweight='bold', color='#f56802')
    ax.tick_params(axis='y', rotation=0)

    # Format the y-axis labels in thousands
    ax.xaxis.set_major_formatter(ticker.FuncFormatter(lambda x, 
                                                      pos: f'{x/1e3:.1f}K'))

    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

    

def plot_top_brands(pqa_all, n=10):
    """Plots the top n brands with the most questions."""
    # Count the number of questions for each brand
    brand_counts = (pqa_all
                    .groupby('brand_name')
                    .count()
                    .orderBy('count', ascending=False)
                    .limit(n+1)
                    .toPandas())
    
    # Create the vertical bar plot with reversed order
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(8, 6))
    ax.barh(brand_counts['brand_name'][1:][::-1],  # Reverse the order
            brand_counts['count'][1:][::-1],  # Reverse the order of counts
            color=[c_darkorange, c_darkorange, c_darkorange,
                   c_darkorange, c_darkorange, c_darkorange,
                   c_darkorange, c_orange, c_orange, c_darkorange][::-1])
    ax.set_xlabel('Count (Thousands)', fontsize=16)
    ax.set_ylabel('Brand Name', fontsize=16)
    ax.set_title("Tech Talk: 10 Most Discussed Brands in PQA", 
                 fontsize=20, fontweight='bold', color='#f56802')

    # Format the y-axis labels in thousands

    plt.tight_layout()

def plot_top_products(pqa_all, n=10, max_length=25):
    """Plots the top n products with the most questions."""
    # Count the number of questions for each product
    product_counts = (pqa_all
                      .groupby('item_name')
                      .count()
                      .orderBy('count', ascending=False)
                      .limit(n)
                      .toPandas())
    
    # Truncate the item names
    product_counts['item_name'] = product_counts['item_name'].apply(
        lambda x: (x[:max_length] + '...') if len(x) > max_length else x)
    
    # Create the vertical bar plot with reversed order
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(8, 6))
    ax.barh(product_counts['item_name'][::-1],  # Reverse the order
            product_counts['count'][::-1],  # Reverse the order of counts
            color=c_oranges)
    ax.set_xlabel('Count (Thousands)', fontsize=16)
    ax.set_ylabel('Item Name', fontsize=16)
    ax.set_title("Amazon Ruled Top 10 Products in PQA", 
                 fontsize=20, fontweight='bold', color='#f56802')
    ax.tick_params(axis='y', rotation=0)

    # Format the y-axis labels in thousands
    ax.xaxis.set_major_formatter(ticker.FuncFormatter(lambda x, 
                                                      pos: f'{x/1e3:.1f}K'))

    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

def plot_question_answer_distribution(pqa_all):
    """Plots the distribution of question types and aggregated answers."""
    # Select 'question_type' and 'answer_aggregated' columns, 
    # group by these columns, count, order by count, and convert to Pandas
    question_answer_counts = (pqa_all
                            .select('question_type', 'answer_aggregated')
                            .groupby('question_type', 'answer_aggregated')
                            .count()
                            .orderBy(F.desc('count'))
                            .toPandas())

    # Pivot the DataFrame to get counts for each combination of Q and A
    question_type_counts_pivot = (question_answer_counts
                                  .pivot(index='question_type', 
                                         columns='answer_aggregated', 
                                         values='count'))

    # Create the plot
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(8, 6))
    question_type_counts_pivot.plot(kind='bar', 
                                    stacked=True, 
                                    ax=ax, 
                                    color=[c_darkblue, 
                                           c_darkorange, 
                                           c_midorange,
                                           c_orange])
    ax.set_xlabel('Question Type', fontsize=16)
    ax.set_ylabel('Count (Millions)', fontsize=16)
    ax.set_title("N/A and Neutral Answers Make Up 70% of PQA", 
                 fontsize=20, fontweight='bold', color='#f56802')
    ax.tick_params(axis='y', rotation=0)
    
    # Format the y-axis labels in millions
    ax.yaxis.set_major_formatter(ticker
                                 .FuncFormatter(lambda x, 
                                                pos: f'{int(x/1e6):,}M'))  
    ax.yaxis.tick_right()  # Move the y-axis to the right
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()


# Add additional words to stopwords
additional_stopwords = ["will", "one", "come", "want", "know", "see", 
                        "go", "get", "thanks", "thank", "im",
                       "X", "x", "1", "2", "3", "4", "5", "6", "7", "8", "9", 
                       "dont", "mine", "think", "us", "hi", 
                        "hello", "dear", "cant", "ive", "didnt"]

STOPWORDS = STOPWORDS.union(set(additional_stopwords))

# Compile regex patterns for stopwords and punctuation
pattern = re.compile(r'\b(' + r'|'.join(STOPWORDS) + r')\b\s*')
re_stop = udf(lambda x: re.sub(pattern, '', x))
pattern_punc = re.compile(r'[^\w\s]')
re_punc = udf(lambda x: re.sub(pattern_punc, '', x))

def word_cloud_plot(pqa_all, title, wc_column, is_answer=False):
    """Plot word cloud"""

    # If the column is 'answers', we need to handle it differently
    if is_answer:
        df_tokens = (pqa_all
                    .select(explode(split(re_stop(lower(re_punc(col(wc_column)
                    .getItem(0).cast("string")))), " ")).alias("tokens"))
                    .filter(col('tokens') != '')
                    .filter(length('tokens') > 1)
                    .groupby("tokens")
                    .count()
                    .orderBy(desc("count"))
                    .limit(150)
                    .toPandas())
    else:
        # Tokenize the input DataFrame, remove stopwords and punctuation, 
        # group by tokens, count, and order by count
        df_tokens = (pqa_all
                    .select(explode(split(re_stop(re_punc(
                        lower(wc_column)))," "))
                    .alias("tokens"))
                    .filter(col('tokens') != '')
                    .groupby("tokens")
                    .count()
                    .orderBy(desc("count"))
                    .limit(150)
                    .toPandas())

    # Create a dictionary to store word frequencies
    d = {}
    for a, x in df_tokens.values:
        d[a] = x

    # Generate the word cloud
    wordcloud = WordCloud(background_color="white", colormap='autumn')
    wordcloud.generate_from_frequencies(frequencies=d)

    # Plot the word cloud
    fig = plt.figure(figsize = (10, 5))
    plt.title(f"Word Cloud on {title}",
              fontsize=20, fontweight='bold', color='#f56802')
    plt.imshow(wordcloud, interpolation="bilinear")
    plt.axis("off")
    plt.show()

4. DATA COLLECTION

The first step in the data collection methodology is to retrieve the necessary data. In this case, we will focus on accessing the Amazon-PQA dataset, which contains customer questions and corresponding answers regarding products on Amazon. This dataset holds valuable insights into customer queries, preferences, and concerns.

The three key steps involved in data collection section are as follows:

  • Identifying the data source
  • Describing the data
  • Collecting the data

4.1 Data Source

The primary dataset for this study is the Amazon Product Questions and Answers (Amazon-PQA) dataset, which consists of an extensive collection of customer queries and responses in August 2020 related to a diverse range of Amazon products. This dataset was sourced from AWS OpenData and was originally used in the study "Answering Product-Questions by Utilizing Questions from Other Contextually Similar Products," authored by (Rozen et al., 2021) and presented at the 2021 Conference of the North American Chapter of the Association for Computational Linguistics: Human Language Technologies.

The Amazon PQA dataset is stored in an S3 bucket with Amazon Resource Name arn:aws:s3:::amazon-pqa located in the us-east-1 region. It consists of 100 JSON files, each representing a different product category. The total uncompressed size of the dataset is 17.3 GB.

4.2 Data Description

In this subsection, the data dictionaries of each dataset are summarized, providing details about the description, and data type of each feature. This aids in understanding the data and identifying any data quality issues that may require preprocessing.

Table 2 provides a summary description of the relevant features used in this study.

Data from Amazon-PQA Dataset: (Amazon PQA)

  • Number of Data Points: 9,989,014
  • Number of Features: 15
Table 2. Data Description of Features Used
Variable Name Description Data Type
question_id Question identifier String
question_text Full question text String
answers Full answer text String
asin Product identifier String
bullet_point1 to bullet_point5 Product bullet points containing additional or more detailed product description String
product_description Product description String
brand_name Product brand name String
item_name Product title String
question_type Question type classification of whether it's a yes-no question or a WH (Who, What, When, Where, Why, How) question String
answer_aggregated Yes, No, or Neutral answers for yes-no question_type and N/A for WH question_type String
product_category Product category String

These fields collectively provide a comprehensive understanding of the product in question and the customer queries associated with it. The dataset is meticulously organized by categories, providing a structured format that supports efficient data analysis.

s3 = boto3.resource('s3')
bucket = s3.Bucket('amazon-pqa')

# Get list of all .json files in the bucket
json_files = ([obj
               .key for obj in bucket
               .objects
               .all() if obj.key.endswith('.json')])

# Extract product category from file name
product_categories = ([os
                       .path
                       .basename(file)
                       .replace('amazon_pqa_', '')
                       .replace('.json', '') for file in json_files])

# Initialize an empty dataframe same as the defined schema
pqa_all = spark.createDataFrame([], schema)

# Loop over all files
for json_file in json_files:
    # Read the json file from S3
    df = spark.read.json("s3a://amazon-pqa/" + json_file)
    
    # Extract product category from the filename
    product_category = (os
                        .path
                        .basename(json_file)
                        .replace('amazon_pqa_', '')
                        .replace('.json', ''))
    
    # Add the product category as a new column
    df = df.withColumn('product_category', lit(product_category))
    
    # Concatenate the dataframe with the main dataframe
    pqa_all = pqa_all.union(df)

This could be because these types of questions are straightforward and easy for customers to ask and for others to answer.

6. DATA ANALYSIS AND VISUALIZATION

The data analysis and visualization section aims to uncover valuable insights from the dataset using various analytical techniques and visualization tools. This section utilizes Apache Spark DataFrame, Pandas, and Matplotlib to perform descriptive analytics and gain a comprehensive understanding of the data. The following key aspects will be addressed:

Descriptive Analytics:

  • Utilize Apache Spark DataFrame to explore the dataset.
  • Analyze questions and answers by product category, brand, item names, and other relevant features to gain insights from the data.

Data Visualization:

  • Visualize the results of the analysis to enhance comprehension and communication of key findings.
  • Utilize appropriate charts, graphs, and plots to present patterns, trends, and relationships in the data.
  • Create meaningful visual representations of the features for an interpretable communication of insights.

6.1 Top 10 Product Categories

plot_top_product_categories(pqa_all)
Figure 2. Plot Top 10 Product Categories

COMMENTS/INSIGHTS:

  • High Interest in Tech Products: Figure 2 reveals that the majority of the top 10 product categories are tech-related, including unlocked cell phones, earbud headphones, traditional laptops, tablets, portable bluetooth speakers, and streaming media players. This suggests a high level of customer engagement and queries in these areas, indicating a strong interest or potential issues that need addressing.

  • Accessories and Basic Cases: The presence of basic cases and accessories in the top categories suggests that customers are not just interested in the main products, but also in complementary items. This could indicate a need for bundled offers or more detailed information on compatibility and features of these accessories.

  • Batteries and Games: The inclusion of batteries and games in the top 10 indicates specific areas where customers might have more questions or concerns, possibly due to performance or compatibility issues.

These insights can be leveraged to improve product descriptions by focusing on areas where customers have the most queries. For customer service, understanding the common issues in these top categories can help in training representatives and preparing resources. For marketing strategies, these insights can guide the promotion of products and bundles that are likely to attract customer interest. The existence of complementary items in the top 10 indicates potential cross-selling opportunities where relevant accessories can be recommended to customers during their purchasing journey, ultimately enhancing customer satisfaction and increasing revenue.

6.4 Plot Distribution By Question Type

In [17]:
# Plot Distribution By Question Type
plot_question_type_distribution(pqa_all)
Figure 5. Plot Distribution By Question Type

COMMENTS/INSIGHTS:

The distribution of question types, as shown in Figure 5, reveals that there is a nearly equal split between "yes-no" type questions and "WH" type questions (those starting with 'what', 'where', 'when', 'why', 'who', 'which') through which we noted the following:

  • Balanced Distribution: The nearly equal distribution of yes-no and WH type questions suggests that customers are not only seeking confirmation or denial (which is typically the case with yes-no questions) but are also interested in obtaining detailed information or explanations (which is often the case with WH questions). This indicates a diverse range of customer curiosity and information needs.

  • Product Descriptions The high number of WH questions could imply that product descriptions may not be providing enough detailed information that customers are seeking. This could be an opportunity to improve product descriptions by incorporating more detailed and specific information about the products.

  • Customer Service The high number of yes-no questions suggests that customers often need quick confirmations or clarifications. This could be an opportunity to enhance customer service by providing quick and direct responses to such queries.

6.5 Plot Distribution By Aggregated Answers

In [18]:
plot_question_answer_distribution(pqa_all)
Figure 6. Plot Distribution By Aggregated Answers

COMMENTS/INSIGHTS:

Continuing with the insights listed in Figure 5, we further examined the distribution of answers (answers_aggregated) for each question type, leading to the following insights:

  • Complex Nature of WH Questions: The majority of 'WH' type questions (who, what, where, when, why, how) tend to have non-binary answers, indicated by the 'N/A' category. This suggests that these questions require more detailed or subjective responses, reflecting their complexity.

  • Neutrality of Yes-No Questions: A significant portion of 'yes-no' type questions are labeled as 'neutral'. This suggests that these questions either remain unanswered or receive non-definitive 'yes' or 'no' responses. Attention should be given to address these neutral answers as they indicate a potential gap in customer satisfaction or seller's hesitance to provide clear responses.

  • Positive Trend in Yes-No Responses: There are more 'yes' answers than 'no' answers for 'yes-no' type questions. This indicates a favorable trend, suggesting that customers often seek confirmation or affirmation rather than raising concerns or objections.

Considering the distribution of question types and aggregated answers in Figure 6, the following additional insights emerge:

  • Lack of Definitive Answers for WH Questions: Many responses for WH question types fall under 'N/A' and yes-no question types under 'neutral', indicating the absence of clear-cut responses. This can be attributed to the complexity of the questions, limited information available, or the subjective nature of the queries. 'N/A' answers are acceptable for WH questions, but it is important to address the neutral responses in 'yes-no' questions to provide clarity to customers and reduce uncertainties.

  • Emphasizing Product Description: The higher number of "yes" responses compared to "no" responses in 'yes-no' questions suggests that customers often seek confirmation or validation. This highlights the importance of including relevant information in product descriptions to address common customer queries and reduce the need for confirmation.

7. RESULTS AND DISCUSSION

Our analysis of the Amazon PQA dataset yielded several key insights into the nature of customer queries and the products they pertain to.

  • Product Category and Brand Name: The most common product category was unlocked_cell_phones, indicating a high level of customer engagement in this area. However, the most common brand name was an empty string, suggesting that many products are unbranded or the brand is not specified. This could be due to the product being generic or the brand name being irrelevant to the question or answer.

  • Item Name and Question Type: The item with the most questions was the Fire TV Stick with Alexa Voice Remote, suggesting that this product generates a lot of customer interest or has unclear product descriptions. The most common type of question was yes-no, indicating that customers often seek binary responses.

  • High Interest in Tech Products: The majority of the top 10 product categories were tech-related, suggesting a strong customer interest in these areas. This could indicate a need for more detailed information on these products or potential issues that need addressing.

  • Brand Dominance: The top brands in the dataset were well-known tech giants such as Amazon, Samsung, ASUS, Sony, HP, Apple, Acer, and Dell. This indicates that these brands dominate the market and are the most discussed among customers.

  • Amazon's Own Products: The top 10 most discussed products were all Amazon's own products, particularly those related to its Echo and Fire product lines. This suggests that these products generate a significant amount of customer interaction and engagement.

  • Question Types and Answers: There was a nearly equal split between yes-no type questions and WH type questions, suggesting a diverse range of customer curiosity and information needs. Many responses for WH question types fell under N/A and yes-no question types under neutral, indicating the absence of clear-cut responses.

  • Word Cloud Analysis: The word clouds of questions, responses, and product descriptions provided insights into the common features, attributes, and issues highlighted by customers and sellers. Customers often asked about the functionality, compatibility, and specifications of the products, while sellers highlighted a wide range of product features in their descriptions and responses.

These insights can be leveraged to improve product descriptions, customer service, and marketing strategies. For instance, product descriptions could be improved by incorporating more detailed and specific information about the products. Customer service could be enhanced by providing quick and direct responses to customer queries. Marketing strategies could be guided by the promotion of products and bundles that are likely to attract customer interest.

8. CONCLUSION

The analysis of the Amazon PQ&A dataset has provided valuable insights into customer queries and product information. By understanding the most common product categories, brands, and items that customers inquire about, we were able to identify key areas of customer interest and potential confusion. The prevalence of tech-related products and brands in customer queries highlights the need for clear and comprehensive product descriptions in these areas.

Furthermore, the analysis of question types and responses revealed a diverse range of customer curiosity and information needs. The nearly equal distribution of yes-no and WH type questions suggests that customers are seeking both binary responses and detailed information. The absence of clear-cut responses to many of these questions indicates a potential gap in product information and customer service.

The word cloud analysis of questions, responses, and product descriptions further emphasized the importance of detailed product information. Customers often ask about product functionality, compatibility, and specifications, while sellers highlight a wide range of product features in their descriptions and responses.

By comprehending and examining the findings of this study and continuously striving to address customers' actual needs, Amazon and retailers can enhance their offerings by providing comprehensive and precise product information, delivering prompt and direct responses to customer inquiries, and showcasing products and packages that are likely to captivate customer attention. Adopting this customer-centric approach will not only amplify customer satisfaction but also drive revenue growth, establishing a mutually beneficial solution for both customers and the business.

9. RECOMMENDATION

9.1 Data Assumptions and Limitations

The analyses presented in this report are based on a set of underlying assumptions and limitations associated with the data. Key assumptions and limitations identified during the creation of this report are as follows:

Assumptions:

  • The data quality and integrity are assumed to be reliable, with minimal missing values and inaccuracies.
  • The data collected is assumed to be unbiased and reflective of customers' actual experiences and opinions.
  • The dataset is assumed to be a representative sample of all Amazon customer queries. However, it's important to note that the dataset may not cover all product categories or brands equally.
  • The analysis assumes that the frequency of queries about a product or brand is indicative of its popularity or complexity. However, it could also be influenced by other factors such as the product's market presence or advertising efforts.
  • The classification of questions into 'yes-no' and 'WH' types assumes that these categories adequately capture the nature of customer queries. However, some questions may not fit neatly into these categories.

Limitations:

  • The dataset only includes queries and responses from Amazon, limiting the generalizability of the findings to other e-commerce platforms.
  • The analysis does not account for temporal trends. Customer queries and concerns may change over time due to factors such as product updates, market trends, or seasonal variations.
  • The word cloud analysis provides a high-level overview of the most common words but does not capture the context or sentiment of the queries and responses. This has been added in recommendations for future work.
  • The dataset might not include a comprehensive representation of all customer interactions and feedback, as it may be limited to specific channels or sources and geographical locations.
  • There could be potential selection bias in the dataset, as it may not cover all demographic segments or regions equally.
  • The analysis relies solely on the available variables in the dataset, which may not encompass all relevant factors that impact customer behavior or preferences.
  • External factors beyond the dataset, such as market conditions or competitive landscape, may influence customer behavior and outcomes but are not considered in the analysis.

9.2 For Immediate Implementation

  • Improve Product Descriptions: Based on the high frequency of questions about product functionality, compatibility, and specifications, sellers should ensure that their product descriptions are clear, comprehensive, and detailed. They should particularly focus on tech-related products, which were among the top queried categories. A formula for structuring product descriptions could be:

    • [Product Name] + [Key Features] + [Specifications] + [Compatibility Information] + [Usage Instructions] + [Support and Warranty Information]

  • Enhance Customer Service: Sellers should provide quick and direct responses to customer queries, particularly 'yes-no' type questions which often seek confirmation or clarification. They should also address the neutral responses in 'yes-no' questions to provide clarity to customers and reduce uncertainties. Continuously update the product description anytime a new question has an answer that is a key information about the product to minimize the same questions from being raised again in the future.

  • Optimize Marketing Strategies: Sellers should leverage the insights about the most queried products and brands to focus their marketing efforts. They could promote products and bundles that are likely to attract customer interest, such as tech products and their accessories. They could also recommend relevant accessories to customers during their purchasing journey, enhancing customer satisfaction and increasing revenue.

9.3 For Future Work

  • Conduct Temporal Analysis: Future work could explore how customer queries and concerns change over time. This could provide insights into temporal trends and help sellers anticipate and address seasonal variations in customer queries.

  • Expand Analysis to Other Platforms: The analysis could be extended to other e-commerce platforms to compare customer queries and improve the generalizability of the findings.

  • Incorporate Sentiment Analysis: Future work could incorporate sentiment analysis to understand the tone of the queries and responses. This could provide additional insights into customer satisfaction and areas of concern.

  • Personalize Customer Service: Based on the patterns in customer queries, sellers could develop personalized customer service strategies. For instance, they could provide tailored product recommendations or support resources based on the types of questions a customer asks.

  • Test and Refine Recommendations: The recommendations provided should be tested and refined based on their effectiveness. Sellers could conduct A/B testing to compare different product description formats, customer service practices, or marketing strategies and identify the most effective approaches.

  • Utilize Natural Language Processing Topics:

    • Topic Modeling: Perform topic modeling (like LDA) on the answers to group them into different topics. This could provide more detailed insights into what the common themes or topics are in the answers.

    • Sentiment Analysis: Perform sentiment analysis on the answers to understand the overall sentiment (positive, negative, neutral) of the responses.

    • Further Text Cleaning: Further clean the text data by removing more stopwords or non-informative words that don't contribute much to the meaning of the answers.

    • N-grams: Instead of looking at individual words, look at bigrams (two-word phrases) or trigrams (three-word phrases). This could provide more context and reveal more about the topics discussed in the answers.

    • Term Frequency-Inverse Document Frequency (TF-IDF): This could be used to identify the importance of different words in the dataset. Words that appear frequently in a document but not across documents would have a high TF-IDF score.
